{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_bullock_ver01/data/sn82016181/00516999627/1938012601/0698.xml":{"full_text":"Keep Wages Up,\nCut Prices, Is\nF. D/s Demand\n(See Editorial on Page 14)\nBy United Press\nPresident Roosevelt was prepared today to resume\npump-priming Federal spending to maintain national\npurchasing power against any general industrial wage\nreduction in the next five months.\nHe warned \u201cthose who be\nlieve in the profit system\u201d that\nthey should maintain wages\nand cut prices to expand mar\nkets for their goods.\nRoosevelt stated his wage\nand price policies at his press\nconference yesterday in a reply\nto what he interpreted as in\nsistence by Benjamin Fairless.\nU. S. Steel Corporation presi\ndent, that steel prices could not\nbe reduced without cutting\nwages. The President said he\nwas opposed to wage reduc\ntions but warned mass produc\ntion industries, and especially\nthe steel industry, to meet de\npression problems by cutting\nprices in search of larger sales\nvolumes.\n\u2018THOSE WHO GET\n\u201cBut that does not mean,\u201d Roose\nvelt said, \u201cthat such price reductions\ncan come out of wages. Those who\nbelieve in the profit system must\nrecognize that those who get the\nprofits when business is good must\nbear the losses when business tempo\nrarily is slack.\nThose who get the\nprofits when industry gets the volume\nare the ones to bear the risk of such\nprice reductions as may be necessary\nto stimulate and restore volume.\nI\n\u201cThose in charge of a well-managed\nand solvent industry should no more\nconsider casting the burden of a\ntemporary business recession upon,\ntheir workers than upon their bond-\nholders. To cast such burden on the\nbondholders is financial bankruptcy.\nTo cast such burden on its workers\nis not only moral bankruptcy, but\nit is bankruptcy of sound business\njudgment.\n\u201cIf industries reduce wages this\n2--1, 41 .1 1.\nwinter and spring, they will be de\nliberately encouraging the withhold-\ning of buying\u2014they will be fostering\na downward spiral and they will\nmake it necessary for their Govern\nment to consider other means of cre\nating purchasing power.\u201d\nRoosevelt amplified his prepared\nstatement slightly by saying that\nthere were some industries in which\nprices assuredly could be reduced\nwithout cutting wages.\nAsked to\nname those industries, the President\npreferred merely to hold that there\nwere lots of them.\nANNUAL WAGE THEORY\nRoosevelt said the problem now was\nto increase, not decrease, national\npurchasing power toward restoration\nof prosperity. He said there may be\nsome special hourly wage situations\nin the building trades in some areas\nwhich \u201cmay call for different treat\nment\u201d so far as yearly earnings are\ni\nBut he explained that\nconcerned.\nany application of the annual wage\ntheory to those hourly wage struc\ntures would be to increase the yearly\nreturn of workers, despite the implied\ndesire to reduce hourly rates deemed\nto be so high that they interfere with\nrevival of the construction industry.\nThe President told questioners that\nThomas W. Lamont of J. P. Morgan\nCo., John L. Lewis of the Commit\ntee for Industrial Organization. Owen\nD. Young of General Electric, who\nrecently met with him, had individ\nually expressed belief that wage lev-:\nels should be maintained. Lewis yes\nterday in a speech before the con-'\n\nvention of his United Mine Workers'\nof America said he would oppose any j\nplan to meet business recession by.\nprice cuts or wage reductions. Roose-\nvelt felt, however, that he and Lewis:\nwere in substantial agreement on the\nwage-price issue.\nNavy War Games Scheduled\nLOS ANGELES, Jan. 26\u2014Navy of\nficials revealed yesterday that more\nthan 100 warships of the United\nStates fleet will be anchored behind;\nthe breakwater Monday to test the I\ncapacity of Los Angeles\u2019 man-made j\nharbor as a protected war base. I\nChinese Seize\nthe Offensive\nBy United Press\nSHANGHAI, Jan. 26\u2014The C hinese high command has ordered a general offen\nsive against Japanese by guerrilla fighters in the far northwest, Chinese sources\nsaid today.\nIt was said that the offensive already had started in Suiyuan Province, north\nof the (heat Wall, and Chinese reported that guerrillas in Shensi Province, im\nmediately south of the wall, were co-operating.\nLeague Council Meets\nin Apprehensive Mood\nBy United Press\nGENEVA, Jan. 26\u2014The 100th meeting of the League\nof Nations Council began today with Italy absent and\nGreat Britain and France trying to keep smaller na\ntions in active co-operation.\nSince the last meeting, Italy had\u2019\nwithdrawn and her chair at the coun\ncil table was empty.\nThe council opened its meeting\nprivately, arranging its agenda of 26\nitems.\nThe general desire among the big\nnations seemed to be to make sure\nthat the council meeting would be a\nshort one and would take no impor\ntant action.\nSuch troublous problems as the po\nsition of Jews in Rumania, recogni-\ntion of Italy's conquest of Ethiopia\nand the growing demand for reform\nof the League covenant were in the\nSome delegates held\nbackground.\nthat, with Italy newly joining Ger-\nmany and Japan in a boycott of the\nleague, this was not the time for con\ntroversial action.\nUNUSUALLY\nLOW PRICES ON\nGENUINE RINGLETTE\nPERMANENT WAVES\nNO TOP HEAVY HEATERS\nSpecially Priced. S3.95\nExpert Beauty Service 25c\nI\nOATIORAL BERUTY SALON\n629 12th N. W\nMEt 8128\nWOODWARD LOTHROP\n10TA 11th F AND G Streets\nPHONE DISTRICT 5300\nI\nRoomy\u2014Easy to Open\u2014Protective\nThe New Odora\nDrop-Door Wardrobe\nI\nI\n.98\nPress a button\u2014the door\nslides easily down. A spring\nsteel lock holds it when shut.\nPlenty of room at the bot\ntom for blankets and fold\naway garments.\nNo swing\ning doors to take up unneces\nsary room. Full-length Odora\nRetainer gives off a refresh\ningly pungent odor\u2014much to\nmoths\u2019 discouragement. The\nsturdy lacquered frame and\nuprights are reinforced with\nmetal corners. 2 feet wide, 22\ninches deep, 5 feet high.\nHOUSEWARES, FIFTH FLOOR\nTalon Maker\u2019s Rites Set\nMEADVILLE. Pa., Jan. 26\u2014Funeral\nservices were to be held today in the\nMeadville Congregational Church for\nCol. Lewis M. Walker. 82, president\nand founder of Talon. Inc., pioneer\nmaker of hookless fasteners. He died\nMonday.\nThe order was attributed to\na desire to take advantage of\nthe withdrawal of Japanese\ntroops from points in\nthe\nnorthwest, and at the same\ntime prevent further withdraw\nals of Japanese troops to\nstrengthen the armies driving\non Hsuchow, the important\nrailroad junction on the north\nsouth Tientsin-Nanking line\nand the east-west Lunghai line\nin central China.\nThis new Chinese move was co\nincident with Chinese assertions that\ntheir men were operating with suc\ncess against the Japanese on the\nHsuchow front and in the Wuhu area,\nup the Yangtse from Nanking.\nForeign military observers here re\npolled that the Chinese were sending\nstrong reinforcements to the Hsu\nchow front.\nWoodward lotiirop\n10\" It\u2122 F AMI G STEeTs\nPHOvE DIstt 5300\n.'J\n1 I\n1\ny\nThe Kleinert\nEasy Way to Reduce Safely\nWear the Kleinert Sturdiflex foundation of\nperforated rubber. It gently massages super\nfluous flesh through normal exertion of\neveryday activities.\nWith Swami brassiere\ntop of rayon and adjustable shoulder\nstraps and garters (illustrated above).\n$2\nWear\nKleinert\u2019s\nprotection\u2014they\nBraform for perspiration\nare\nlaundered and come\nto 12 (sketched right)\neconomical,\nin\nsizes\n3.\neasily\n2 $1.25\nNOTIONS, AISLE 21, FIR-T FLOOR","height":"21280","width":"14520"}}
